The office of the public protector has poked holes in President Jacob Zuma’s assertion that former incumbent Thuli Madonsela “dictated” to him that he appoint a commission of inquiry into allegations of state capture.
Zuma’s advocate‚ Ismail Semenya‚ had argued in the Pretoria High Court earlier yesterday that Madonsela had encroached on executive authority in directing Zuma to appoint the commission‚ saying this amounted to dictating to the president to do what the constitution empowered only him to do.
But Advocate Vincent Maleka, counsel for the public protector‚ said Madonsela’s remedial actions only required Zuma to fulfil his constitutional responsibility under section 84 of the constitution.


“Secondly‚ we will show that [Zuma] has a constitutional obligation to assist the public protector to take a remedial action that is effective.
“So when the public protector devised this remedy‚ she did not purport to dictate to the president‚ she required him to fulfil his constitutional obligation to assist [her] to give effectiveness to that remedy.”
Zuma is seeking to set aside Madonsela’s directive that he appoint a commission of inquiry. The report recommended the presiding judge be chosen by Chief Justice Mogoeng Mogoeng.


